\begin{center}
{\Large \bf  Home Work 10 ---- E84, Fall, 2004}
\end{center}
\begin{enumerate}

\item Find the gain of the Op-amp circuit shown below. Find the 
input impedance.

\htmladdimg{../hw10b.gif}

{\bf Solution:}

\[ V_A=V_{in}\frac{R_1}{R_1+R_2},\;\;\;\;
   V_B=V_{out}\frac{R_3}{R_3+R_4} \]
but as $V_A\approx V_B$, we get
\[V_{out}=\frac{R_3+R_4}{R_3} \frac{R_1}{R_1+R_2} V_{in} \]


\item The circuit shown below is used as a 3-bit digital to analog 
(D/A) converter. The inputs $V_0$, $V_1$, $V_2$ are the three bits 
of a binary number (0V for 0 and 5V for 1), and the output $V_{out}$
is the corresponding analog value proportional to the binary input.
Express the output $V_{out}$ as a function of the three inputs.

\htmladdimg{../hw10a.gif}

{\bf Hint:} Apply KCL to points A, B, and C (in that order), and 
represent $V_{out}$ in terms of $V_2$, $V_1$ and $V_0$ (through 
$V_B$ and $V_A$).

{\bf Solution:}
\begin{itemize}
\item KCL to A: 
  \[ \frac{V_0-V_A}{2R}=\frac{V_A}{2R}+\frac{V_A-V_B}{R},
  \;\;\;\;\; V_0=4V_A-2V_B  \]
\item KCL to B:
  \[ \frac{V_1-V_B}{2R}+\frac{V_A-V_B}{R}=\frac{V_B}{R},
  \;\;\;\;\; V_1=5V_B-2V_A  \]
\item Combine the two equations above to get
  \[ 8V_B=V_0+2V_1 \]
\item KCL to C:
  \[ \frac{V_2}{2R}+\frac{V_B}{R}=-\frac{V_{out}}{8R},
  \;\;\;\;\; V_{out}=-(4V_2+8V_B)=-(4V_2+2V_1+V_0) \]
\end{itemize}  

\end{enumerate}

